MUSA508: Predicting Bike Share Demand in Philadelphia

Jenna Epstein

11/12/2020

Introduction

In recent years, bike share programs have become a prominent form of micro-mobility in cities. While some dock-less programs have emerged, several cities still rely on docking station networks as points for riders to pick-up and drop-off bikes. For commuters and students, bikes provide an alternative, sustainable form of transit that provides flexibility. These bike share programs, however, are not useful if the number of bikes at each dock does not meet the demand of riders. Especially during peak commute times, this could have negative implications on the customer base, ranging from simple frustrations, to verbal complaints, to complete abandonment of program membership. It is thus in the best interest of bike share operators to accommodate demand of their customers, and rebalance the bike share bikes accordingly.

This analysis looks at bike share ridership in Philadelphia in August 2018 to forecast space/time demand for bike pickups. Data is provided by Indego, the bike share program in the city. By using a summer month, when weather is relatively pleasant and there are no holidays affecting typical transit and commute patterns, the goal is for it to be more generalizable to bike share demand in other months.

To meet bike share demand in Philadelphia, I envision a plan to specifically focus on meeting the demands of commuters in the morning and evening. This will require deployment of fleet vehicles to reallocate the bikes across popular docking stations, ensuring that there are enough bikes before the morning and evening rushes. In summer months, customers may want to ride to their places of work during earlier or later hours when the temperature is lower. This will impact the scheduling for Indego truck drivers, and likely require some coordination with planners or even the city to figure out the most optimal routes for large vehicles to drive on.

The development of an algorithm to help predict bike share demand is a key piece to help inform Indego’s operational plans for resource allocation and how to maximize efficiency. While there may be alternate ways of gauging demand from frequent riders - like asking customers to indicate future trips in the Indego app - the company should not rely on user input and self-reporting. Leveraging the existing data to predict for future demand would provide greater accuracy and confidence for Indego as they spend time and resources for re-balancing.

NOTE: The year 2018 is selected due to availability of US Census Bureau, American Community Survey estimates (they are only accessible through 2018 via the API)

  theme(
    text = element_text( color = "black"),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 13,colour = "black"),
    plot.subtitle=element_text(face="italic"),
    plot.caption=element_text(hjust=0),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),axis.title = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill=NA, size=2),
    strip.text.x = element_text(size = 14))}

q5 <- function(variable) {as.factor(ntile(variable, 5))}

# Helper Functions
qBr <- function(df, variable, rnd) {
  if (missing(rnd)) {
    as.character(quantile(round(df[[variable]],0),
                          c(.01,.2,.4,.6,.8), na.rm=T))
  } else if (rnd == FALSE | rnd == F) {
    as.character(formatC(quantile(df[[variable]]), digits = 3),
                          c(.01,.2,.4,.6,.8), na.rm=T)
  }
}

Import Data

First, bike share data for Indego - Philadelphia’s official bike share program - is imported. The datasets are available by quarter, so after reading in the full set of trips for quarter 3 of 2018, the data is filtered to only include the month of August. Before creating any new variables, the bike share stations are joined with Philadelphia neighborhoods (data comes from opendataphilly.org). Each station is assigned to the neighborhood polygon that it sits within.

New variables are created also to associate each trip’s start time with an interval of 15 minutes and of 60 minutes. Week and day of the week (dotw) variables are also created at this time based on these new intervals.

Data from the US Census Bureau’s American Community Survey is loaded at this time, and some socioeconomic variables Percent_White, Mean_Commute_Time, and Percent_Taking_Public_Trans are created to use later in the analysis. The Census data is then joined to the bike trips data.

Additionally, the weather-related data is loaded in for Philadelphia during this designated month of August 2018. Data for precipitation, wind speed, and temperature comes from the station at the Philadelphia International Airport.

bikeTrips <- read.csv("indego-trips-2018-q3.csv", na.strings=c("", "NA")) %>%
  filter(str_detect(start_time,"2018-08")) %>%
   tidyr::drop_na()

bikeTrips2 <- bikeTrips %>%
  mutate(interval60 = floor_date(ymd_hms(start_time), unit = "hour"),
         interval15 = floor_date(ymd_hms(start_time), unit = "15 mins"),
         week = week(interval60),
         dotw = wday(interval60, label=TRUE))

phillyCensus <- 
  get_acs(geography = "tract", 
          variables = c("B01003_001", "B19013_001", 
                        "B02001_002", "B08013_001",
                       "B08012_001", "B08301_001",
                        "B08301_010", "B01002_001"), 
          year = 2018, 
          survey = "acs5",
          state = "PA", 
          county = "Philadelphia",
          geometry = T, 
          output = "wide",
          cb=F) %>%
  rename(Total_Pop =  B01003_001E,
         Med_Inc = B19013_001E,
         Med_Age = B01002_001E,
         White_Pop = B02001_002E,
         Travel_Time = B08013_001E,
         Num_Commuters = B08012_001E,
         Means_of_Transport = B08301_001E,
         Total_Public_Trans = B08301_010E) %>%
  select(Total_Pop, Med_Inc, White_Pop, Travel_Time,
         Means_of_Transport, Total_Public_Trans,
         Med_Age,
         GEOID, geometry) %>%
  mutate(Percent_White = White_Pop / Total_Pop,
         Mean_Commute_Time = Travel_Time / Total_Public_Trans,
         Percent_Taking_Public_Trans = Total_Public_Trans / Means_of_Transport)

phillyTracts <- 
  phillyCensus %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  distinct(GEOID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  select(GEOID, geometry) %>% 
  st_sf
bikeTrips_census <- st_join(bikeTrips2 %>% 
          filter(is.na(start_lon) == FALSE &
                   is.na(start_lat) == FALSE &
                   is.na(end_lat) == FALSE &
                   is.na(end_lon) == FALSE) %>%
          st_as_sf(., coords = c("start_lon", "start_lat"), crs = 4326),
        phillyTracts %>%
          st_transform(crs=4326),
        join=st_intersects,
              left = TRUE) %>%
rename(Origin.Tract = GEOID) %>%
  mutate(start_lon = unlist(map(geometry, 1)),
         start_lat = unlist(map(geometry, 2)))%>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  select(-geometry)%>%
  st_as_sf(., coords = c("end_lon", "end_lat"), crs = 4326) %>%
  st_join(., phillyTracts %>%
            st_transform(crs=4326),
          join=st_intersects,
          left = TRUE) %>%
  rename(Destination.Tract = GEOID)  %>%
  mutate(end_lon = unlist(map(geometry, 1)),
         end_lat = unlist(map(geometry, 2)))%>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  select(-geometry)
weather.Panel <- 
  riem_measures(station = "PHL", date_start = "2018-08-01", date_end = "2018-09-01") %>%
  dplyr::select(valid, tmpf, p01i, sknt)%>%
  replace(is.na(.), 0) %>%
    mutate(interval60 = ymd_h(substr(valid,1,13))) %>%
    mutate(week = week(interval60),
           dotw = wday(interval60, label=TRUE)) %>%
    group_by(interval60) %>%
    summarize(Temperature = max(tmpf),
              Precipitation = sum(p01i),
              Wind_Speed = max(sknt)) %>%
    mutate(Temperature = ifelse(Temperature == 0, 42, Temperature))

This graph shows the bike share trips per hour. The pattern appears consistent - the line peaks and troughs likely correspond to trips in the day versus in the night. There are also lower periods during the weekends.

To delve into this further, these histograms show the mean number of hourly trips per bike share station, grouped by time of day: Morning Rush, Mid-Day, Evening, and Overnight. The long tail of the distribution for the evening rush shows that there is more variation in when people take bike trips. This is likely due to different working hours and variation in commutes. There are fewer trips mid-day, which makes sense given that it is during typical work hours for many people in the city. Overnight has the tightest distribution with very few trips, which is expected.

Exploratory Analysis

Create the Space/Time Panel

Before diving deeper into more feature engineering and exploratory analysis, a space/time panel containing an observation for every possible space/time combination is created.

length(unique(bikeTrips_census$interval60)) * length(unique(bikeTrips_census$start_station))

study.panel <- 
  expand.grid(interval60=unique(bikeTrips_census$interval60), 
              start_station = unique(bikeTrips_census$start_station)) %>%
  left_join(., bikeTrips_census %>%
              select(start_station, Origin.Tract, start_lon, start_lat, trip_route_category, passholder_type) %>%
              distinct() %>%
              group_by(start_station) %>%
              slice(1))

#nrow(study.panel)   
ride.panel <- 
  bikeTrips_census %>%
  mutate(Trip_Counter = 1) %>%
  right_join(study.panel) %>% 
  group_by(interval60, start_station, Origin.Tract, start_lon, start_lat, trip_route_category, passholder_type) %>%
  summarize(Trip_Count = sum(Trip_Counter, na.rm=T)) %>%
  left_join(weather.Panel) %>%
  left_join(phillyCensus, by = c("Origin.Tract" = "GEOID"))%>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(is.na(start_station) == FALSE) %>%
  mutate(week = week(interval60),
         dotw = wday(interval60, label = TRUE)) %>%
  filter(is.na(Origin.Tract) == FALSE) %>%
    mutate(weekend = ifelse(dotw %in% c("Sun", "Sat"), "Weekend", "Weekday")) %>%
   st_sf()

Time Lags

Now that ride.panel is created, some feature engineering to create time lag variables will help to understand bike share demand during specific hours of a day (and the day before). No federal holidays occurred in August 2018, so there is no need to control for any additional day-specific lags. the following time lags are created:

  • lagHour: a time lag of one hour
  • lag2Hours: a time lag of two hours
  • lag3Hours: a time lag of three hours
  • lag4Hours: a time lag of four hours
  • lag12Hours: a time lag of twelve hours (expecting an opposite demand for bikes)
  • lag1day: a time lag of twenty-four hours (expecting the a similar demand for bikes)
ride.panel <- 
  ride.panel %>% 
  arrange(start_station, interval60) %>% 
  mutate(lagHour = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,1),
         lag2Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,2),
         lag3Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,3),
         lag4Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,4),
         lag12Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,12),
         lag1day = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,24)) %>%
   mutate(day = yday(interval60))

These correlations for each of these lags are shown below, both in the table and the scatterplots. The lagHour variable has the strongest correlation (r=0.77). The predictive power decreases as the hours go by, with the lag12Hours correlation being negative. For the lag1day, though, it goes back up (r=0.77), confirming the expectation that there would be similar demand around the same time on the next day.

plotLags <- as.data.frame(ride.panel) %>%
    group_by(interval60) %>% 
    summarise_at(vars(starts_with("lag"), "Trip_Count"), mean, na.rm = TRUE) %>%
    gather(Variable, Value, -interval60, -Trip_Count) %>%
    mutate(Variable = factor(Variable, levels=c("lagHour","lag2Hours","lag3Hours","lag4Hours",
                                                "lag12Hours","lag1day")))

correlation.lag <-
    group_by(plotLags, Variable) %>%
    summarize(correlation = round(cor(Value, Trip_Count, use = "complete.obs"), 2)) 
    correlation.lag %>% kable(caption="Time Lag Correlations") %>% kable_styling()

Trip Count Spatial Autocorrelation

Since the bike trip data is joined to the census tracts, visualizing the trip count aggregated by census tract may be useful for understanding the spatiality of demand for bikes in the city.

The first series of maps shows the sum of bike share trips aggregated by Census Tract of origin for each of the weeks in the ride.panel. In week 34, the bottom-most census tract jumps from the first quintile to the second quintile, but the next week it jumps back down. This change looks especially magnified, though, because of the size of the Tract. There are three Indego stations in this tract, but they are concentrated towards the top-middle of the Tract. This shows that Census Tract aggregation of trip counts by station may distort perception of where demand is situated.

NOTE: Not all Census Tracts in Philadelphia have an Indego station; the maps with Census Tracts only show those that have at least one station.

Distance to Center City

The maps above show that there are concentrations of bike trips in Census Tracts in the center of the city, so a feature is engineered for Euclidian distance to the center (as a centroid) of the Center City neighborhood.

ride.panel %>% st_as_sf(coords = c("start_lon", "start_lat"), crs = 4326, agr = "constant")
  
nhoods <- st_read("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/azavea/geo-data/master/Neighborhoods_Philadelphia/Neighborhoods_Philadelphia.geojson") %>% st_transform(st_crs(ride.panel))

ccPoint <-
  filter(nhoods, name == "CENTER_CITY") %>%
  st_centroid()
  
ride.panel$ccDistance =
  st_distance(st_centroid(ride.panel),ccPoint) 
#%>% as.numeric()

Time of Day

It seems that including the time_of_day variable as a permanent part of the dataset may help with bolstering predictive power of the model later on; so it is created again as a permanent feature and joined to ride.panel. The four bins are Overnight, AM Rush, Mid-Day, and PM Rush.

ride.panel <- ride.panel %>%
    mutate(hour = hour(interval60),
      time_of_day = case_when(hour(interval60) < 7 | hour(interval60) > 18 ~ "Overnight",
                                 hour(interval60) >= 7 & hour(interval60) < 10 ~ "AM Rush",
                                 hour(interval60) >= 10 & hour(interval60) < 15 ~ "Mid-Day",
                                 hour(interval60) >= 15 & hour(interval60) <= 18 ~ "PM Rush"))

Space/Time Correlation

To visualize both the space and the time correlations simultaneously, two animated gifs help visualize these dependencies in the city. They both use bike share trip data from one Monday - August 13, 2018 - over 15 minute intervals. The first one groups the bike trip data by census tract, adding up the total number of trips for all of the stations in each tract. The second shows the bike trip data for each station specifically. In both cases, the animations show a concentration of trips in the center of the city.

week33 <-
  filter(bikeTrips_census, week == 33 & dotw == "Mon")

week33.panel <-
  expand.grid(
    interval15 = unique(week33$interval15),
    Origin.Tract = unique(bikeTrips_census$Origin.Tract))

ride.animation.data_tract <-
  mutate(week33, Trip_Counter = 1) %>%
    right_join(week33.panel) %>% 
    group_by(interval15, Origin.Tract) %>%
    summarize(Trip_Count = sum(Trip_Counter, na.rm=T)) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    left_join(phillyTracts, by=c("Origin.Tract" = "GEOID")) %>%
    st_sf() %>%
    mutate(Trips = case_when(Trip_Count == 0 ~ "0 trips",
                             Trip_Count > 0 & Trip_Count <= 3 ~ "1-3 trips",
                             Trip_Count > 3 & Trip_Count <= 6 ~ "4-6 trips",

The temperature data shows there was a bit of a cold spike towards the end of August, but it is not related to the precipitation peak, or fluctuations in wind speed. In the modeling portion of this analysis, these variables will be incorporated to see if they improve the predictive power or not.

Modeling and Testing

In this section, linear models are created and tested on partitioned dataset. Once a model is chosen, the errors are explored. Then, the chosen model is cross-validated using the “leave-one-group-out” method, based on bike station. The cross-validation uses the full five-week panel of data.

Split data to train and test

The five-week data is split into a training set (first three weeks) and a test set (last two weeks) of the August 2018 bike trips.

ride.Train <- filter(ride.panel, week < 34)
ride.Test <- filter(ride.panel, week >= 34)

Running Models

After exploring Poisson regression, Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) regression is better for this data. There are many data points in this month of trips, so it should work well for accuracy. Here, four linear models are created using the lm function and the training data ride.Train.

reg1 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature,  data=ride.Train)

reg2 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start_station + dotw + Temperature,  data=ride.Train)

reg3 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start_station + hour(interval60) + dotw + time_of_day + passholder_type + Temperature + Precipitation, 
     data=ride.Train)

reg4 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start_station + hour(interval60) + Temperature  + dotw  + time_of_day + trip_route_category + lagHour + lag2Hours + lag12Hours + lag1day + ccDistance,
     data=ride.Train)

Predicting for Test Data

Next, a nested dataframe is created to house the test data by week. The purr package is used here, which contains functions to loop through the nested data and compare across model specifications.

library(purrr)
ride.Test.weekNest <- 
  ride.Test %>%
  nest(-week) 

model_pred <- function(dat, fit){
   pred <- predict(fit, newdata = dat)}
week_predictions <- 
  ride.Test.weekNest %>% 
    mutate(A = map(.x = data, fit = reg1, .f = model_pred),
           B = map(.x = data, fit = reg2, .f = model_pred),
           C = map(.x = data, fit = reg3, .f = model_pred),
           D = map(.x = data, fit = reg4, .f = model_pred)) %>% 
    gather(Regression, Prediction, -data, -week) %>%
    mutate(Observed = map(data, pull, Trip_Count),
           Absolute_Error = map2(Observed, Prediction,  ~ abs(.x - .y)),
           MAE = map_dbl(Absolute_Error, mean, na.rm = TRUE),
           sd_AE = map_dbl(Absolute_Error, sd, na.rm = TRUE))

  • Day of the week (dotw)
  • Station of origin (start_station)
  • Hour (hour(interval60)
  • Distance to the centroid of Center City (ccDistance)

Cross Validation

To test the generalizability of the model, a LOGO (leave one group out) cross-validation on the five-week panel (ride.panel) is performed, leaving out a station for each of the 100 folds. This will also help test the accuracy across stations.

#load the r cross validate function

crossValidate <- function(dataset, id, dependentVariable, indVariables) {

allPredictions <- data.frame()
cvID_list <- unique(dataset[[id]])

for (i in cvID_list) {

  thisFold <- i
  cat("This hold out fold is", thisFold, "\n")

  fold.train <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] != thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
                dplyr::select(start_station, week, interval60, indVariables, dependentVariable, start_lat, start_lon)
  fold.test  <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] == thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
                dplyr::select(start_station, week, interval60, indVariables, dependentVariable, start_lat, start_lon)
  
regression <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start_station + hour(interval60) + Temperature  + dotw  + time_of_day + trip_route_category +
                   lagHour + lag2Hours + lag12Hours + lag1day + ccDistance,
     data=ride.panel)

  thisPrediction <- 
    mutate(fold.test, Prediction = predict(regression, fold.test, type = "response"))
    
  allPredictions <-
    rbind(allPredictions, thisPrediction)
    
  }
  return(allPredictions)
}
# reg.vars
reg.vars <- c("start_station", "interval60", "dotw", "Temperature", "lagHour", "lag2Hours",
              "lag12Hours", "lag1day", "ccDistance", "time_of_day", "trip_route_category")

# crossValidate
reg.SpatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = ride.panel,
  id = "start_station",
  dependentVariable = "Trip_Count",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
  dplyr::select(cvID = start_station, Trip_Count, Prediction, interval60, dotw, start_lat, start_lon, ccDistance,trip_route_category, time_of_day)

The histogram below shows the distribution of errors for the LOGO cross-validation. There are a few errors that are much higher than others, but for the most part, the distribution hovers between 0 and 0.1. The higher errors are likely skewing the error distribution.

# reg summary
reg.summary <- 
    mutate(reg.SpatialCV, Error = Prediction - Trip_Count,
                          Regression = "LOGO-CV")
# calculate errors
error_by_fold <- 
  reg.summary %>%
    group_by(cvID, start_lon, start_lat) %>% 
    summarize(Mean_Error = mean(Prediction - Trip_Count, na.rm = T),
              MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T),
              SD_MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup()

## plot histogram of OOF (out of fold) errors
error_by_fold %>%
  ggplot(aes(MAE)) + 
    geom_histogram(bins = 30, colour="black", fill = "#238A8DFF") +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0)  + 
    labs(title="Distribution of Mean Absolute Error", subtitle = "LOGO-CV",
         x="Mean Absolute Error", y="Count")

To visualize these mean absolute errors by station, they are plotted on the map below. The higher errors are clustered around the center of the city, again showing that the model does not generalize as well to Center City and surrounding areas as it does to stations in West Philadelphia (and also a bit to the south).

  reg.summary %>%
    group_by(cvID, start_lon, start_lat) %>% 
  summarize(Mean_Error = mean(Prediction - Trip_Count, na.rm = T),
              MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T),
              SD_MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T)) %>% ungroup() %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("start_lon", "start_lat"), crs = 4326, agr = "constant")

  ggplot()+
  geom_sf(data = phillyCensus, color = "grey", fill = "transparent")+
  geom_sf(data=error_by_fold_for_map, aes(color = MAE), 
             fill = "transparent", size = 2)+
  scale_colour_viridis(direction = -1,
  discrete = FALSE, option = "D")+
  ylim(min(bikeTrips_census$start_lat), max(bikeTrips_census$start_lat))+
  xlim(min(bikeTrips_census$start_lon), max(bikeTrips_census$start_lon))+
  labs(title="Mean Absolute Errors, by Station",
  subtitle="LOGO Cross-Validation")+
  mapTheme()

Conclusion

Overall, the model performs better when generalized across station contexts, as shown by the lower mean absolute errors by station in the cross-validation compared to the model on its own. While the predictions are better in certain areas of the city (West Philadelphia and South Philadelphia Census Tracts with stations), it is not consistent across space. Furthermore, the model does not predict as well for peak times, and it underpredicts during the evening commute hours, when demand is higher. If Indego leveraged this model to re-allocate bikes in the evening times to Center City, for instance, the under-predictions would mean that they do not supply enough bikes to accommodate the number of riders seeking them. This could have negative implications for their business, as customers may seek other forms of transportation.

To improve this model, additional feature engineering to better pinpoint the factors affecting ridership is recommended. This is especially pertinent for the Center City area, where there may be some additional ridership patterns, demographics, or amenities at play. While the time lag variables did add some predictive power to the model, the distance to the center of the Center City neighborhood hardly influenced the model. In short, it is not recommended to use this algorithm to re-balance the bike share allocation based on ridership demand until the predictive power improves. Specifically, further investigation into the nuances of Center City ridership - beyond what already exists in the Indego dataset and time lag features - is warranted.
